					<dd class="comment byuser comment-author-wbrounds bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-1458">
<p>Hi Allan,</p>
<p>There was a <a href="http://www.gata.org/node/7689" rel="nofollow">case</a> that addressed this exact issue in the District Court in Nevada in 2009. (US v. Kahre, CR-S-05-121-DAE-RJJ).  The defendant was convicted for using gold coins for transactions in exchange for goods and services while only recording the value of those transactions to be the legal tender value of the coins.  </p>
<p>An example would be receiving income in the form of a 1 oz. gold coin.  The current intrinsic value of the gold is around $1,500 but the legal tender face value is only $50. According to the Kahre case, if you only report $50 of income you would be breaking the law.  You should report $1,500.  </p>
<p>It looks like the rule is to report the higher of either the intrinsic value or the face value for tax purposes.  I think this rule is a bunch of garbage, but not following it could land a person in prison.  You may want to review the Godfather for strategies when dealing with overzealous prosecutors.</p>
<p>I hope this helps.</p>
<p>Bill</p>
</div>
					</dd>
