					<dd class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-1462">
<p>You&#8217;re wrong about the facts and law in the NotHaus case. The original four-count indictment included a fraud charge and no &#8220;original design&#8221; allegation. The superceding indictment dropped the fraud charge, but added the original design allegation. This case was only about counterfeiting. This case exemplifies a wrongful conviction, unfortunately there is no DNA evidence to prove to those who &#8220;wish the defendant guilty&#8221; that in fact he is innocent.</p>
</div>
					</dd>
					<dt class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-1465">
<span class="avatar"></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-1465" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">4</a></span>
<span class="comment_author">Bobby Emory</span>
<span class="comment_time">May 12, 2011 at 10:22 pm</span>

					</dt>
					<dd class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-1465">
<p>There may be someone to overturn the &#8220;original design&#8221; part.</p>
<p>Disney sells silver coins.</p>
<p>They have lots of lobbyists in D.C.  If someone points out this problem to Disney, they will get the law changed.</p>
<p>Bobby</p>
</div>
					</dd>
					<dt class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-1470">
<span class="avatar"></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-1470" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">5</a></span>
<span class="comment_author">Bill</span>
<span class="comment_time">May 17, 2011 at 6:18 am</span>

					</dt>
					<dd class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-1470">
<p>BvN also profited by selling the merchants the rounds for a profit over his cost, but still at a discount to the face value of the LD round.</p>
<p>His whole scheme then encouraged the merchants to offer that LD coin as change, when the silver value in that round was well under the face value on the LD round.</p>
<p>How is that not intentional?</p>
<p>Note that if the customer wanted silver they could have bought a silver American Eagle, plus had enough change left over for another half-ounce.</p>
<p>So in the above example they would have profited even more from silver&#8217;s rise in value than those customers foolish enough to accept a<br />
LD round as change.</p>
<p>Note that privately minted silver rounds have always commanded less of a premium than the silver American Eagle.</p>
</div>
					</dd>
					<dt class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-2050">
<span class="avatar"></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-2050" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">6</a></span>
<span class="comment_author">Cliff Case</span>
